ing test class structure**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to use forkEvery=1 to broaden my tests project, but it seems like it might only suit certain situations. The idea of splitting into nested static test classes could work, but I need to stick to the rule of one-to-one mapping between report classes and generated test class files. Also, creating two top-level public tests could create issues, especially with JUnit. I wonder if there’s a way to modify Gradle to help with managing forks effectively.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing resource handling**\\n\\nI’m exploring whether resetting is necessary since ResourceBundle.getBundle is called in both overloads when msgs is null. But what happens if a key is missing? In that case, msgs might not be null. I wonder if I can invoke one overload in a Java test and the other in a native test, considering dynamic-access coverage. It seems like coverage reports and dynamic access might be merging from different test tasks, but I’m curious about how this affects method calls across runtimes.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring native image behavior**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how a native image runtime call could cover specific lines in the executable, but I need to be cautious about using guards. It seems forbidden to skip Native Image execution when using those guards. I wonder if branching based on system properties is a way to manage different behaviors, although it's likely prohibited. There's also the consideration that coverage reports might only reflect JVM agents, not native, but I could use JUnit's lifecycle to manage execution properly in both contexts.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test class structure**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to maintain a clear structure between dynamic-access report classes and the generated test class files. One file can have both a test class and a helper that isn't a test, right? I guess we can include a public top-level `CompatibilityTest`, but what about helper classes? If a helper has a main method and isn’t a test, can it be package-private? I feel like all top-level test classes should definitely be public, while a non-test class can be package-private.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating process coverage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether forking a child process might lack coverage, especially if an agent isn't linked to that child. That's not ideal. I'm also considering launching the same code in a new thread while adjusting the static state, but that doesn't seem right. I wonder if `ResourceBundle.getBundle` doesn't cache the object. The msgs field could be null if it returns null, but it never does. Let's take a look at the dynamic report format to check coverage by line.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3VBjKtSCSZQRSZzfe4W0CLfT|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fd9d4688197a72d68ad2a3a954c", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3155, "output": 1174, "cacheRead": 19968, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24297, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780391877194, "responseId": "resp_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fc5f4e08197a0acb6e8cf56d539"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_3VBjKtSCSZQRSZzfe4W0CLfT|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fd9d4688197a72d68ad2a3a954c", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"classes\" : [ {\n    \"callSites\" : [ {\n      \"covered\" : false,\n      \"frame\" : \"org.eclipse.swt.awt.SWT_AWT.lambda$0(SWT_AWT.java:147)\",\n      \"line\" : 147,\n      \"metadataType\" : \"reflection\",\n      \"trackedApi\" : \"java.lang.Class#forName(java.lang.String)\"\n    }, {\n      \"covered\" : false