[thinking] **Considering testing compatibility**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I'm thinking about working with JVM and how Native Image handles dynamic class loading, which isn't supported. Tests should run natively, but using a classloader approach that needs reflection to call methods seems problematic. I could set Gradle's test configuration to `forkEvery = 1`, but I wonder how to run two methods with forks. Nested test classes might be treated separately by Gradle, and JUnit requires non-static inner classes, which adds some complexity. I need to verify how Gradle scans compiled test files.
[thinking] 
[thinking] **Analyzing Gradle test detection**
[thinking] 
[thinking] I think Gradle's test class detection processes all class files, excluding abstract ones, and might include inner classes. It seems JUnit can run static nested tests, but the @Nested annotation needs to be non-static. If I set `forkEvery=1`, then maybe only the outer class has one fork that includes all nested classes, which doesn't feel reliable. I could explore creating two public top-level test classes in the same Java file, but Java rules say only one must be public—though package-private tests might conflict with that. Am I overlooking something?
[thinking] 
