which adds some complexity. I need to verify how Gradle scans compiled test files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Gradle test detection**\\n\\nI think Gradle's test class detection processes all class files, excluding abstract ones, and might include inner classes. It seems JUnit can run static nested tests, but the @Nested annotation needs to be non-static. If I set `forkEvery=1`, then maybe only the outer class has one fork that includes all nested classes, which doesn't feel reliable. I could explore creating two public top-level test classes in the same Java file, but Java rules say only one must be public—though package-private tests might conflict with that. Am I overlooking something?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_GqGNGWRgrmAC5VapF34H6oWn|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fe703ac8197828fa2584c0482bd", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"getMessage|msgs|SWTMessages|Compatibility\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata-copy/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/main/extracted/org/eclipse/swt | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 14188, "output": 805, "cacheRead": 10752, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 25745, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780391898374, "responseId": "resp_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fdb28d881979425b69e6e4b8344"}}
