[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering testing compatibility**\n\nI'm thinking about working with JVM and how Native Image handles dynamic class loading, which isn't supported. Tests should run natively, but using a classloader approach that needs reflection to call methods seems problematic. I could set Gradle's test configuration to `forkEvery = 1`, but I wonder how to run two methods with forks. Nested test classes might be treated separately by Gradle, and JUnit requires non-static inner classes, which adds some complexity. I need to verify how Gradle scans compiled test files.\n\n**Analyzing Gradle test detection**\n\nI think Gradle's test class detection processes all class files, excluding abstract ones, and might include inner classes. It seems JUnit can run static nested tests, but the @Nested annotation needs to be non-static. If I set `forkEvery=1`, then maybe only the outer class has one fork that includes all nested classes, which doesn't feel reliable. I could explore creating two public top-level test classes in the same Java file, but Java rules say only one must be public—though package-private tests might conflict with that. Am I overlooking something?", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fdbd24c81979ef7f6506a7ae2ca\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqHp_n2Voucu6gmaLjDYI_sdPmWWTND1YZE0_-5NOsOhgaDBoKySdWmmYw3E9VemguagwZFbj7O6RRtQ21atgFWMZOnWpiX70mS69chEcyey2eAvAiWrcjRSoogrIzXRIQ5uTki1KYFy9fMQJ61gGv9tieySxP7vMUIV7tD4TyQ7Or3XORVhzuJ3t0E5ph3D0FHHW6aZZuQKDTDK5EVSrPIT85QTaKk6bzEXS7jYge6zCZIumPcU8uh_HZXYtVWFGaY9m1OwfhPC0V3EJjPl2jNSm770JI3Gs_2RbjvRpWOGhFxg665yv8vfe5iFf_2nOab7b95QULwH0N1IeDBYTgn-Uo1vpBYh0JSKWYyr19SIK7KSPTyqOcHoTkhQ60uauGCR_ExtJGKdilCLYCZvgCeXZWZpkbS0UUPposS51iyBoQ69mG2Ioopiw1cmYbJdv2Urebjl0sdRBVKbnbUSNDuDsmSRZIJ9J8qeeb0ka_vcpmoTtYhc_VnNXJtMiwFMBKsBJCoeIanfmJrFCpbukKDIfCCPMjqf6RuYblegLMyzVhc7bjIH2khzHC8bxn2tjQS95bXjVC